Where do I copy the file path from? How do I find that?

To use the index.html code I provided for your GitHub Pages website, you need to update the file paths in the code to point to your uploaded drone photos (e.g., in the images/ folder) and zip files (e.g., in the data/ folder). This is tailored to your goal of creating a website for drone photography and data files, assuming you’re using the GitHub web interface.

What is a File Path?

A file path in this context is the location of a file in your GitHub repository, relative to the root of the repository. For example:

  • If you upload a photo named myphoto1.jpg to the images/ folder, its path is images/myphoto1.jpg.
  • If you upload a zip file named myproject1.zip to the data/ folder, its path is data/myproject1.zip.

You’ll use these paths in the index.html code to link to your images and zip files.

Steps to Find and Copy File Paths on GitHub

Here’s how to find the file paths for your uploaded files in your GitHub repository (yourusername.github.io):

  1. Upload Your Files to GitHub:
    • Go to your repository on GitHub (e.g., https://github.com/yourusername/yourusername.github.io).
    • Create the necessary folders if you haven’t already:
      • Click “Add file” > “Create new file.”
      • Name it images/.gitkeep to create an images/ folder (GitHub requires a file to create a folder). Commit the file.
      • Repeat for data/.gitkeep to create a data/ folder.
    • Upload your files:
      • Navigate to the images/ folder by clicking on it.
      • Click “Add file” > “Upload files,” then drag and drop your drone photos (e.g., myphoto1.jpg, myphoto2.jpg) or select them. Click “Commit changes.”
      • Navigate to the data/ folder and upload your zip files (e.g., myproject1.zip) the same way.
    • Ensure file names are simple (no spaces or special characters, e.g., use my-photo.jpg instead of My Photo!.jpg) to avoid issues.
  2. Locate a File in Your Repository:
    • In your repository, navigate to the folder containing your file:
      • For a photo, click the images/ folder to see its contents.
      • For a zip file, click the data/ folder.
    • Find the file you need (e.g., myphoto1.jpg or myproject1.zip) in the list.
  3. Copy the File Path:
    • Method 1: Construct the Path Manually:
      • The file path is the folder name followed by the file name. For example:
        • A file myphoto1.jpg in the images/ folder has the path: images/myphoto1.jpg.
        • A file myproject1.zip in the data/ folder has the path: data/myproject1.zip.
      • You can type this path directly when editing index.html. No need to copy anything if you know the folder and file name.
    • Method 2: Copy from GitHub:
      • Click on the file name (e.g., myphoto1.jpg) in the repository to view it.
      • To get the relative path, note the folder and file name in the URL or breadcrumb trail (e.g., yourusername.github.io/images/myphoto1.jpg shows the path is images/myphoto1.jpg).
      • Alternatively, right-click the “Raw” button (or the file download link) and select “Copy link address.” The full URL will be something like https://raw.githubusercontent.com/yourusername/yourusername.github.io/main/images/myphoto1.jpg. Extract the part after /main/ (e.g., images/myphoto1.jpg) for the relative path.
      • Paste this path (e.g., images/myphoto1.jpg) into a text editor or directly into index.html when editing.
  4. Update index.html with the File Paths:

        Repeat for each image, adding more <img> tags if needed.
      • In the <section class="files">, update zip file paths. For example, change:
        html
        <a href="data/project1.zip" download>Project 1 Data (QGIS, Photos, GPX)</a>
        to:
        html

        Add more <li><a> tags for additional zip files.
    • Click “Commit changes” to save.

Tips for Finding File Paths

  • Check Folder Structure: In the GitHub repository, the file list shows the folder hierarchy. If your file is in images/subfolder/myphoto1.jpg, the path is images/subfolder/myphoto1.jpg.
  • Avoid Full URLs: Use relative paths (e.g., images/myphoto1.jpg) in index.html, not full URLs (e.g., https://raw.githubusercontent.com/...), as relative paths work locally within your site.
  • File Name Accuracy: File names and paths are case-sensitive. If you uploaded MyPhoto1.JPG, use images/MyPhoto1.JPG, not images/myphoto1.jpg.
  • Test Paths: If an image or zip link doesn’t work, view the file in GitHub, click “Raw,” and confirm the path. A 404 error usually means the path in index.html doesn’t match the actual file location.

Common Issues

  • File Not Found: If images or zips don’t load, ensure the file exists in the specified folder (e.g., images/) and the path in index.html is correct. Check for typos or incorrect case.
  • File Size Limit: GitHub’s web interface limits uploads to 100 MB per file. If a zip file is larger, split it or use an external host (e.g., Google Drive) and link to it in index.html.
  • Folders Not Created: If images/ or data/ don’t exist, create them using the .gitkeep method before uploading files.

How do I host more data on my website?

To host more data on your GitHub Pages website for your drone photography and QGIS zip files, you need to address GitHub’s storage and file size limitations while maintaining the functionality of your site (e.g., the Metis Crossing site with download links). GitHub Pages, as used for your current setup, has a ~1 GB soft storage limit per repository and a 100 MB file size limit for web uploads (or 2 GB with Git LFS, but with bandwidth constraints). To host more data beyond these limits, you can use strategies within GitHub or combine GitHub Pages with external file hosting services. Below, I’ll outline practical approaches to increase your data capacity, tailored to your goal of making files (drone photos and QGIS zips) available for colleagues to download directly, while keeping the process simple and free.

Current Setup Recap

  • Website: Your GitHub Pages site (yourusername.github.io) uses the index.html code I provided, with two download buttons for drone_photos.zip and qgis_files.zip in a data/ folder, and a background image in images/.
  • Limits:
    • Storage: ~1 GB per repository (soft limit; GitHub may flag larger repos).
    • File Size: 100 MB per file via web interface; 2 GB with Git LFS (1 GB/month bandwidth limit for free accounts).
    • Bandwidth: 100 GB/month for downloads.
  • Goal: Host more data (e.g., additional zip files or larger files) for colleagues to download.

Strategies to Host More Data

Here are free methods to increase your data hosting capacity, starting with GitHub-based solutions and then external services.

1. Use Multiple GitHub Repositories

GitHub’s ~1 GB storage limit applies per repository. You can create additional repositories to store more data and link to their files from your main GitHub Pages site.

Steps:

  • Create New Repositories:
    • Go to github.com, click “+” > “New repository.”
    • Name them descriptively (e.g., drone-data-1, drone-data-2). Make them public or private (if private, ensure colleagues have access).
  • Upload Files:
    • In each new repository, create a data/ folder (e.g., via “Add file” > “Create new file,” name it data/.gitkeep).
    • Upload additional zip files to data/ (e.g., more_drone_photos.zip, qgis_project2.zip) via “Add file” > “Upload files.”
    • Each repository gets ~1 GB, so you could store ~1 GB per repo (e.g., 10 repos = ~10 GB total).
  • Link Files in index.html:
    • Get the “Raw” URL for each file:
      • In a new repo (e.g., drone-data-1), navigate to data/more_drone_photos.zip, click “Raw,” and copy the URL (e.g., https://raw.githubusercontent.com/yourusername/drone-data-1/main/data/more_drone_photos.zip).
    • Update your index.html in yourusername.github.io to include these links. For example, add to the .columns section:
      html
      <div class="column"> <h2>More Drone Photos</h2> <a href="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/yourusername/drone-data-1/main/data/more_drone_photos.zip" download>Download Zip</a> </div>
    • Edit index.html via GitHub: Click it, use the pencil icon, paste the updated code, and commit.
  • Advantages:
    • Stays within GitHub ecosystem.
    • Each repo adds ~1 GB, and there’s no limit on the number of repositories for free accounts.
  • Downsides:
    • Managing multiple repos can be tedious.
    • External URLs may not look as clean as local paths (e.g., data/drone_photos.zip).
    • Still subject to 100 MB file size limit per file (or 2 GB with Git LFS).

Example: If you have 5 GB of zip files, split them across 5 repositories (~1 GB each). Link all files in your index.html for centralized access.

2. Use Git LFS for Larger Files

If your zip files exceed 100 MB but are under 2 GB, Git LFS (Large File Storage) allows larger uploads, but free accounts are limited to 1 GB of storage and 1 GB/month bandwidth for LFS files.

Steps:

  • Set Up Git LFS:
    • Install Git LFS locally (requires Git; see Git LFS docs).
    • In your repository, run git lfs install and git lfs track "*.zip" to track zip files.
    • Commit and push changes.
  • Upload Files:
    • Add zip files (up to 2 GB each) locally, commit, and push to your yourusername.github.io repository.
    • Files go to data/ as before (e.g., data/large_drone_photos.zip).
  • Link in index.html:
    • Use relative paths as usual (e.g., <a href="data/large_drone_photos.zip" download>).
  • Advantages:
    • Handles files up to 2 GB.
    • Integrates with your existing site.
  • Downsides:
    • Only 1 GB total LFS storage for free accounts (shared across all repos).
    • Requires local Git setup, which is more complex than web uploads.
    • Bandwidth limit (1 GB/month) may restrict downloads if colleagues access large files frequently.

Recommendation: Use Git LFS only if you have a few large files and are comfortable with Git. Otherwise, external hosting (below) is simpler.

3. Combine GitHub Pages with External File Hosting

To host significantly more data, use free external file hosting services like Google Drive or Mega for large or numerous zip files, while keeping your GitHub Pages site as the central hub with download links. This bypasses GitHub’s storage limits entirely.

Option A: Google Drive (15 GB Free)

  • Steps:
    • Sign up for a free Google account at drive.google.com.
    • Upload zip files to Google Drive:
      • Click “New” > “File upload,” select your files (e.g., drone_photos_extra.zip).
      • No file size limit, but total storage is 15 GB (shared with Gmail, Google Photos).
    • Generate shareable links:
      • Right-click a file, select “Share,” set to “Anyone with the link,” and copy the link (e.g., https://drive.google.com/file/d/your-file-id/view?usp=sharing).
      • For direct downloads, modify the link to: https://drive.google.com/uc?export=download&id=your-file-id (replace your-file-id with the ID from the original link).
    • Update index.html:
      • Add links to the .columns section or create a new column. Example:
        html
        <div class="column"> <h2>Additional Drone Photos</h2> <a href="https://drive.google.com/uc?export=download&id=your-file-id" download>Download Zip</a> </div>
      • Edit index.html via GitHub: Click it, use the pencil icon, and commit.
  • Advantages:
    • 15 GB free storage, far exceeding GitHub’s ~1 GB.
    • No file size limit per upload.
    • Easy to use with no coding or Git knowledge.
  • Downsides:
    • Direct download links may sometimes redirect to a Google Drive page (browser-dependent).
    • External links may look less integrated than local paths.

Option B: Mega (20 GB Free)

  • Steps:
    • Sign up at mega.nz.
    • Upload zip files:
      • Click “Upload” > “File,” select your files.
      • Total storage is 20 GB (base limit; may vary with bonuses).
    • Generate shareable links:
      • Right-click a file, select “Get link,” set to “Anyone with the link,” and copy the URL (e.g., https://mega.nz/file/your-file-id).
    • Update index.html:
      • Add Mega links similarly to Google Drive links:
        html
        <div class="column"> <h2>Additional QGIS Files</h2> <a href="https://mega.nz/file/your-file-id" download>Download Zip</a> </div>
  • Advantages:
    • 20 GB free storage.
    • Reliable direct downloads.
    • Encrypted file sharing.
  • Downsides:
    • Requires colleagues to access Mega, which may prompt sign-ups for large downloads.
    • Slightly less familiar than Google Drive.

Example index.html Update: To add a third column for additional files on Google Drive or Mega, modify the .columns section in your index.html:

html
<div class="columns"> <div class="column"> <h2>Drone Photos</h2> <a href="data/drone_photos.zip" download>Download Zip</a> </div> <div class="column"> <h2>QGIS Files</h2> <a href="data/qgis_files.zip" download>Download Zip</a> </div> <div class="column"> <h2>Extra Drone Photos</h2> <a href="https://drive.google.com/uc?export=download&id=your-file-id" download>Download Zip</a> </div> </div>

Adjust the CSS .column width (e.g., width: 30%) to fit three columns comfortably.

4. Optimize Existing Files

To maximize space within your current repository, compress files to reduce their size, allowing you to host more data without hitting the ~1 GB limit.

Steps:

  • Compress Images:
    • Use TinyPNG to compress your background image (images/background.jpg) and any drone photos in zips, reducing file size while maintaining quality.
    • Example: A 5 MB image may compress to 1 MB.
  • Compress Zip Files:
    • Use tools like 7-Zip or WinRAR to create smaller zips with maximum compression.
    • Split large zips (>100 MB) into parts (e.g., drone_photos.part1.zip, drone_photos.part2.zip) using 7-Zip’s “Split to volumes” option, each under 100 MB.
    • Upload parts to data/ and link them in index.html:
      html
      <div class="column"> <h2>Drone Photos Part 1</h2> <a href="data/drone_photos.part1.zip" download>Download Zip</a> </div>
  • Remove Unnecessary Files:
    • Review your repository for unused files (e.g., old images) and delete them to free up space.
  • Advantages:
    • Stays within your existing setup.
    • No external services needed.
  • Downsides:
    • Limited by the ~1 GB cap.
    • Compression may not suffice for large datasets.
    • Splitting zips requires colleagues to recombine parts.

5. Alternative Platforms for Larger Storage

If GitHub’s limits are too restrictive, consider hosting your entire site on a platform with more storage, though this may require rebuilding the site.

  • Google Sites + Google Drive:
    • Create a free site at sites.google.com.
    • Add download links to Google Drive files (15 GB).
    • Embed images or create a simple page with buttons similar to your current layout.
    • Pros: 15 GB storage, no file size limit, no coding needed.
    • Cons: Less customizable than GitHub Pages, no direct HTML control.
  • Mega + Wix (Free Plan):
    • Host files on Mega (20 GB).
    • Create a free site at wix.com with download links to Mega files.
    • Pros: 20 GB storage, visual builder.
    • Cons: Wix free plan has 500 MB site storage and ads, less flexible for large data.

These platforms are simpler but may not match GitHub Pages’ clean integration with your current index.html.

can you place zip files within a zip file?

Yes, you can place zip files within a zip file, creating a nested zip archive. This is a common practice known as archiving multiple zip files into a single zip file, and it’s supported by most compression tools like 7-Zip, WinRAR, or the built-in zip utilities in Windows, macOS, and Linux. However, there are practical considerations for your use case of hosting zip files on your GitHub Pages website (e.g., the Metis Crossing site) for colleagues to download. Below, I’ll explain how to do this, the benefits and limitations, and how it impacts your goal of hosting more data within GitHub’s ~1 GB repository limit and 100 MB per-file limit. I’ll also address whether this helps increase the number of zip files you can host, tying into your previous question about capacity.

Can You Place Zip Files in a Zip File?

  • Technically: Yes, you can add one or more zip files (e.g., drone_photos_1.zip, qgis_files_1.zip) into another zip file (e.g., all_project_data.zip). The outer zip file treats inner zip files as regular files, preserving their structure.
  • Tools: Use software like:
    • 7-Zip (Windows/Linux, free): Right-click files, select “Add to archive,” choose .zip.
    • WinRAR (Windows, trial/free): Similar process.
    • Windows: Right-click, “Send to” > “Compressed (zipped) folder.”
    • macOS: Select files, right-click, “Compress.”
    • Linux: Use zip command (e.g., zip -r all_project_data.zip file1.zip file2.zip).
  • Extraction: Colleagues can unzip the outer file (e.g., all_project_data.zip) to access inner zip files, then unzip those as needed. Most unzip tools (e.g., Windows Explorer, macOS Archive Utility) handle this seamlessly.

Example Process

  1. Create Inner Zip Files:
    • Zip your drone photos into drone_photos_1.zip (e.g., 50 MB).
    • Zip your QGIS data into qgis_files_1.zip (e.g., 50 MB).
  2. Create Outer Zip File:
    • Select drone_photos_1.zip and qgis_files_1.zip.
    • Use 7-Zip: Right-click > “Add to archive,” name it all_project_data.zip, set format to .zip.
    • Result: A single all_project_data.zip (~100 MB, assuming minimal compression of inner zips).
  3. Upload to GitHub:
    • In your yourusername.github.io repository, navigate to data/.
    • Click “Add file” > “Upload files,” upload all_project_data.zip (must be <100 MB for web upload).
    • Update index.html to link it:
      html
      <div class="column"> <h2>All Project Data</h2> <a href="data/all_project_data.zip" download>Download Zip</a> </div>
  4. Colleague Experience:
    • Colleagues download all_project_data.zip from your site (https://yourusername.github.io).
    • They unzip it to get drone_photos_1.zip and qgis_files_1.zip, then unzip those for the actual files.

Benefits

  • Organization: Groups related zip files into one downloadable file, reducing clutter in your data/ folder and index.html links. For example, instead of 10 links for 10 zips, you have 1 link for a nested zip.
  • Single Download: Colleagues download one file instead of multiple, simplifying access for projects with many zips.
  • GitHub File Size Limit: Combines smaller zips into one, potentially staying under the 100 MB web upload limit (e.g., two 45 MB zips into one 90 MB zip).
  • Storage Efficiency: If inner zips are already compressed, the outer zip adds minimal overhead (e.g., a few KB), keeping total size close to the sum of inner zips.

Limitations

  • No Significant Compression: If inner zip files are already compressed (as most zips are, using DEFLATE), the outer zip won’t reduce their size much. For example:
    • drone_photos_1.zip (50 MB) + qgis_files_1.zip (50 MB) ≈ all_project_data.zip (~100 MB).
    • This means nesting doesn’t save space within GitHub’s ~1 GB repository limit.
  • Extraction Complexity: Colleagues must unzip twice (outer zip, then inner zips), which may confuse less tech-savvy users. Include a README.txt in the outer zip explaining:
    text
    Unzip this file to access: - drone_photos_1.zip: Drone imagery - qgis_files_1.zip: QGIS project data Then unzip each file for contents.
  • GitHub File Size Limit: The outer zip must still be <100 MB for web uploads or <2 GB with Git LFS (but LFS is limited to 1 GB total storage and isn’t supported for GitHub Pages downloads). If inner zips total >100 MB, you can’t upload the outer zip via the web interface.
  • Repository Storage: Nesting doesn’t increase the number of zip files you can host within the ~1 GB limit, as the total size remains roughly the same.

Impact on Number of Zip Files

In my previous response, I estimated your GitHub Pages repository can hold ~19 zip files at 50 MB each within the ~1 GB limit (after accounting for index.html and background.jpg). Nesting zip files doesn’t change this significantly:

  • Without Nesting: 19 zips at 50 MB = 950 MB.
  • With Nesting: Combine 19 zips into, say, 5 outer zips (e.g., each containing ~3–4 inner zips of 50 MB). Total size is still ~950 MB + minimal overhead (~1–5 MB for outer zips), so you’re still limited to ~19 inner zip files’ worth of data.
  • Multiple Repositories: As before, create additional repos (each ~1 GB) to host more. For example, 5 repos could hold ~95 inner zip files (19 per repo), whether nested or not.
  • External Hosting: Google Drive (15 GB, ~300 zips at 50 MB) or Mega (20 GB, ~400 zips) remains the best for hosting more data, with or without nesting.

Nesting helps with organization (fewer links in index.html) but doesn’t increase storage capacity, as the total data size is unchanged.

Practical Considerations for Your Website

Method 1: Add Files via GitHub’s Web Interface (Recommended)

This is the easiest way to upload files without installing software. It’s ideal for your static site and small-to-medium files.

Steps

  1. Access Your Repository:
    • Go to github.com and sign in.
    • Navigate to your repository (e.g., yourusername/yourusername.github.io or another repo name you created).
    • You’ll see the repository’s main page, likely empty or with a default README.md.
  2. Create Folders (data/ and images/):
    • GitHub requires folders to exist before uploading files into them. Create data/ and images/:
      • Click “Add file” > “Create new file”.
      • In the “Name your file” field, enter data/.gitkeep (.gitkeep is a placeholder to create an empty folder).
      • Click “Commit new file” (use default commit message).
      • Repeat for images/.gitkeep.
    • Result: You now have data/ and images/ folders.
  3. Upload index.html:
    • On the repository’s main page, click “Add file” > “Create new file”.
    • Name the file index.html.
    • Copy the latest index.html code from my previous response (with the rotating photo gallery) and paste it into the editor.
      html
      <!DOCTYPE html> <html lang="en"> <head> <meta charset="UTF-8"> <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0"> <title>Metis Crossing</title> <!-- CSS and rest of code as provided --> </head> <body> <!-- HTML content as provided --> </body> </html>
    • Click “Commit new file”.
    • Alternatively, if you have index.html saved locally:
      • Click “Add file” > “Upload files”.
      • Drag or select index.html, then click “Commit changes”.
  4. Upload Zip Files (drone_photos.zip, qgis_files.zip):
    • Navigate to the data/ folder by clicking it in the repository.
    • Click “Add file” > “Upload files”.
    • Drag or select drone_photos.zip and qgis_files.zip from your computer.
      • Ensure each file is <100 MB (GitHub’s web upload limit).
      • If larger, split using 7-Zip (“Split to volumes, bytes: 100M”) or host on Google Drive/Mega (see below).
    • Click “Commit changes”.
    • Verify file names match index.html paths (e.g., <a href="data/drone_photos.zip">). If names differ (e.g., drone_photos_1.zip), edit index.html:
      • Click index.html, use the pencil icon, update paths, and commit.
  5. Upload Images (background1.jpg, background2.jpg, background3.jpg):
    • Navigate to the images/ folder.
    • Click “Add file” > “Upload files”.
    • Drag or select background1.jpg, background2.jpg, and background3.jpg.
      • Optimize images to <1 MB each using TinyPNG to save space.
      • Ensure each is <100 MB.
    • Click “Commit changes”.
    • Verify names match the slides array in index.html:
      javascript
      const slides = [ { image: 'images/background1.jpg', caption: 'Metis Crossing 1' }, { image: 'images/background2.jpg', caption: 'Metis Crossing 2' }, { image: 'images/background3.jpg', caption: 'Metis Crossing 3' } ];
      If names differ (e.g., metis_landscape1.jpg), edit index.html’s <script> section.
  6. Enable GitHub Pages:
    • Go to your repository’s “Settings” > “Pages”.
    • Under “Source,” select the “main” branch (or the branch containing your files) and save.
    • Note the site URL (e.g., https://yourusername.github.io), which will be live within minutes.
  7. Test the Site:
    • Visit https://yourusername.github.io.
    • Check:
      • The title (“Metis Crossing”) and Metis theme (red/blue).
      • Download buttons work (click to download drone_photos.zip, qgis_files.zip).
      • The gallery rotates every 5 seconds, showing each image with captions (“Metis Crossing 1,” “Metis Crossing 2,” “Metis Crossing 3”).
    • If anything fails (e.g., broken links or missing images), verify file paths in index.html match the repo’s data/ and images/ contents (case-sensitive).
  8. Share with Colleagues:
    • Share the URL (https://yourusername.github.io) via email, Slack, etc.
    • For direct downloads, share “Raw” URLs (e.g., https://raw.githubusercontent.com/yourusername/yourusername.github.io/main/data/drone_photos.zip).

Method 2: Add Files via Command Line (Optional)

If you have many files, prefer version control, or need to upload files >100 MB (up to 2 GB with Git LFS), use Git locally. This requires more setup but offers flexibility.

Prerequisites

  • Install Git for your OS.
  • Optional: Install Git LFS for files >100 MB.
  • Basic command-line knowledge.

Steps

  1. Clone the Repository:
    • Open a terminal (Command Prompt, PowerShell, or Terminal).
    • Run:
      bash
      git clone https://github.com/yourusername/yourusername.github.io.git cd yourusername.github.io
    • This creates a local copy of your repo.
  2. Create Folder Structure:
    • Create data/ and images/ folders:
      bash
      mkdir data images
  3. Add Files:
    • Copy index.html, drone_photos.zip, qgis_files.zip to the data/ folder, and background1.jpg, background2.jpg, background3.jpg to the images/ folder using your file explorer or commands:
      bash
      cp /path/to/drone_photos.zip data/ cp /path/to/background1.jpg images/
    • If files are >100 MB, enable Git LFS:
      bash
      git lfs install git lfs track "*.zip" "*.jpg" git add .gitattributes
  4. Stage and Commit Files:
    • Stage all files:
      bash
      git add .
    • Commit changes:
      bash
      git commit -m "Add index.html, zip files, and gallery images"
  5. Push to GitHub:
    • Upload to your repo:
      bash
      git push origin main
    • If your default branch is master, replace main with master.
  6. Enable GitHub Pages and Test:
    • Follow steps 6–8 from Method 1.

Handling Large Files (>100 MB)

  • GitHub Web Limit: Files must be <100 MB for web uploads. If drone_photos.zip or images exceed this:
    • Split Files: Use 7-Zip to split zips (“Split to volumes, bytes: 100M”). Upload parts (e.g., drone_photos.part1.zip) and link in index.html.
    • External Hosting:
      • Upload to Google Drive (15 GB free):
        • Share file, set to “Anyone with the link,” copy the link, and modify to direct download (e.g., https://drive.google.com/uc?export=download&id=your-file-id).
        • Update index.html:
          html
          <a href="https://drive.google.com/uc?export=download&id=your-file-id" download>Download Zip</a>
      • Or use Mega (20 GB free) with similar linking.
  • Git LFS: Allows 2 GB files but limits free accounts to 1 GB total storage and 1 GB/month bandwidth. Not supported for GitHub Pages downloads, so use for a separate repo if needed.

Troubleshooting

  • Broken Links: If download buttons fail, verify data/drone_photos.zip and data/qgis_files.zip exist in data/. Edit index.html to match file names.
  • Gallery Not Rotating: Ensure background1.jpg, background2.jpg, background3.jpg are in images/ and paths in the slides array are correct (case-sensitive).
  • Site Not Live: Confirm GitHub Pages is enabled in “Settings” > “Pages.” Check the URL after a few minutes.
  • File Size Errors: If uploads fail, confirm files are <100 MB or use external hosting.
  • Storage: Your files (~103 MB for two 50 MB zips + three 1 MB images) fit within the ~1 GB repo limit, leaving ~897 MB for ~17 more 50 MB zips.

Summary

  • Web Interface: Create data/ and images/ folders, upload index.html, zip files, and images via GitHub’s “Add file” options. Enable GitHub Pages, test, and share https://yourusername.github.io.
  • Command Line: Clone the repo, add files locally, commit, and push. Use for large files or bulk uploads.
  • Large Files: Split zips or host on Google Drive/Mega if >100 MB.
  • Next Steps: After uploading, verify the site and share the URL with colleagues. They can download zips without accounts since the repo is public.

If you share your repository name, file names, or encounter issues (e.g., path errors), I can provide specific fixes or updated index.html code. Let me know if you need help with any step!
